Mental Health & Predictable Work Schedules

Schedule Volatility, Front-loading, and Household Wellbeing

Jingyao

24, 2026

data_path <- "C:/Users/jingy/Dropbox/VIP/09. Main study/09. Data/20. Generated/simon_analysis/30_merged_panel-hh_id-period.dta"
if (!file.exists(data_path)) stop("Error: Data file not found at: ", data_path)
data <- read_dta(data_path)
cat("Loaded:", nrow(data), "rows x", ncol(data), "columns\n")
data_analysis <- data %>%
    mutate(
        group_label = case_when(
            control == 1 ~ "Control",
            predictable == 1 & period == 0 ~ "Baseline",
            predictable == 1 & high_draw == 1 ~ "High Draw",
            predictable == 1 & high_draw == 0 ~ "Low Draw",
            TRUE ~ "Unknown"
        ),
        period_label = case_when(
            period == 0 ~ "Period 0 (Baseline)",
            TRUE ~ paste0("Period ", period)
        )
    )
schedule_chars <- data %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period > 0) %>%
    arrange(hh_id, period) %>%
    group_by(schedule) %>%
    summarise(
        prop_high = mean(high_draw, na.rm = TRUE),
        n_switches = mean(
            tapply(high_draw, hh_id, function(x) sum(abs(diff(x)), na.rm = TRUE)),
            na.rm = TRUE
        ),
        front_loading = mean(
            tapply(seq_along(high_draw), hh_id, function(idx) {
                hd <- high_draw[idx]
                w <- rev(seq_along(hd))
                weighted.mean(hd, w = w, na.rm = TRUE)
            }),
            na.rm = TRUE
        ),
        .groups = "drop"
    ) %>%
    mutate(
        volatility_cat = case_when(
            n_switches <= 1 ~ "Low Volatility (<=1 switch)",
            n_switches <= 3 ~ "Medium Volatility (2-3 switches)",
            TRUE ~ "High Volatility (>=4 switches)"
        ),
        timing_cat = case_when(
            front_loading > 0.55 ~ "Front-loaded (High draws early)",
            front_loading < 0.45 ~ "Back-loaded (High draws late)",
            TRUE ~ "Balanced timing"
        ),
        vol_fl = n_switches * front_loading,
        vol_fl_grp = cut(vol_fl,
            breaks = quantile(vol_fl, probs = c(0, 1 / 3, 2 / 3, 1), na.rm = TRUE),
            labels = c("Low composite", "Medium composite", "High composite"),
            include.lowest = TRUE
        )
    )

data_analysis <- data_analysis %>%
    left_join(
        schedule_chars %>%
            select(schedule, volatility_cat, timing_cat,
                   n_switches, front_loading, vol_fl, vol_fl_grp),
        by = "schedule"
    )

1 Introduction

This document investigates whether the shape of an assigned income schedule not just total income causally affects mental health and household wellbeing in the VIP predictable-schedule study.

Each household in the predictable arm is randomly assigned to one of 20 income schedules. Every schedule spans 6 periods and contains exactly 3 High (H) and 3 Low (L) draw periods, so total income is equalized across all households by design. What varies is the ordering of draws. Because assignment is random, any systematic differences in outcomes across schedules must be caused by the schedule shape itself.

The document is organised as follows: Section 2 defines the three schedule-shape measures and presents the main regression results. Section 3 presents the ICC analysis a complementary way to quantify how much outcome variance schedules explain. Sections 47 contain supporting analyses (dynamic effects, mental health trajectories, formal causal tests, and robustness checks).

2 Key Measures and Main Result

2.1 Definitions

We characterise each schedule using three constructed variables. These are computed once per schedule (averaging over all households assigned to it) and then merged into the household-period panel.

n_switches Income Volatility

The number of HL transitions in the 6-period draw sequence. This ranges from 1 (HHHLLL: one HL switch at the midpoint) to 5 (HLHLHL: income alternates every single period). A higher value means a more volatile income path households face frequent reversals between high and low income states. This is the measure most intuitively associated with instability.

Why it matters for mental health: Frequent reversals may cause repeated cycles of raised and dashed expectations. Even if households know their schedule in advance, adapting behaviour to a highly volatile sequence is cognitively and practically demanding.

front_loading Income Timing

A position-weighted mean of the draw sequence, assigning higher weight to earlier periods:

\[\text{front_loading} = \frac{\sum_{t=1}^{6}(7-t)\cdot \mathbf{1}[\text{draw}_t = H]}{\sum_{t=1}^{6}(7-t)} = \frac{6 \cdot d_1 + 5 \cdot d_2 + 4 \cdot d_3 + 3 \cdot d_4 + 2 \cdot d_5 + 1 \cdot d_6}{21}\]

where \(d_t = 1\) if period \(t\) is a High draw and 0 otherwise. Reference values:

Schedule Pattern front_loading
HHHLLL H early 0.71
HLHLHL Alternating 0.57
LLLHHH H late 0.29

A value close to 1 means H draws are concentrated early (front-loaded); close to 0 means H draws come late (back-loaded); 0.5 means balanced timing.

Why it matters: A front-loaded household receives abundant income early but then endures a prolonged stretch of low income potentially feeling like a deprivation relative to earlier periods. The opposite holds for back-loaded households, who might experience low income early as normal, then enjoy a later windfall.

vol_fl Composite Index

\[\text{vol_fl} = n\_switches \times front\_loading\]

This composite is large only when a schedule is both frequently alternating and front-loaded. The intuition: volatile switching is most psychologically disruptive when it begins from a position of early high income the household experiences repeated downward reversals from an established high baseline. A highly volatile but back-loaded schedule partially cancels out, since income starts low and the volatility is less salient. For regression, vol_fl is standardised to mean 0, SD 1.

Summary: vol_fl captures the worst-case schedule shape many switches AND high draws concentrated early. It is our primary summary index, and the decomposition below separates the contribution of each component.

2.2 Regression: Effect of Schedule Shape on Outcomes

We regress each outcome on the standardised composite vol_fl, pooling all 6 treatment periods with period fixed effects and household-clustered standard errors. The sample is restricted to the predictable group. A positive coefficient on PHQ-2 or GAD-2 means worse mental health for households with higher vol_fl (more volatile and front-loaded schedules).

run_pooled <- function(outcome, data) {
    if (!outcome %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
    fml <- as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ vol_fl_std | period"))
    tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = data), error = function(e) NULL)
}

2.3 Decomposition: Volatility vs Front-loading vs Current Draw

The composite vol_fl bundles two distinct schedule features. The table below separates their contributions using five specifications per outcome. This is the main result of the document.

Column Regressors Question answered
(1) vol_fl composite only Does the combined index predict outcomes?
(2) switches n_switches only Is volatility (frequency of switching) sufficient?
(3) front_load front_loading only Is timing (H draws early vs late) sufficient?
(4) decomp both components Which dominates when both are included simultaneously?
(5) full both + high_draw Does schedule shape survive controlling for whether the household is currently in a High draw period?

Column (5) is a robustness check: high_draw = 1 in periods when the household is currently receiving the High income draw. If the effect of vol_fl were purely mechanical simply reflecting that High draw periods have higher income it should disappear once we control for high_draw. Persistence in column (5) indicates genuine structural effects of schedule shape beyond the current-period draw.

data_reg2 <- data_reg %>%
    mutate(
        sw_std = as.numeric(scale(n_switches)),
        fl_std = as.numeric(scale(front_loading))
    )

decomp_outcomes <- c(
    phq2_z                    = "Depression (PHQ-2)",
    gad2_z                    = "Anxiety (GAD-2)",
    total_income_99           = "Total Income",
    total_consumption_99      = "Total Consumption",
    loan_total_outstanding_99 = "Loan Outstanding",
    svg_savings_flow_99       = "Savings Flow",
    days_worked               = "Days Worked"
)

fit_decomp <- function(y, spec) {
    fml <- switch(spec,
        vfl    = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ vol_fl_std               | period")),
        sw     = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std                   | period")),
        fl     = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ fl_std                   | period")),
        decomp = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std + fl_std          | period")),
        full   = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std + fl_std + high_draw | period"))
    )
    tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = data_reg2), error = function(e) NULL)
}

specs  <- c("vfl", "sw", "fl", "decomp", "full")
sp_sfx <- c("(1) vol_fl", "(2) switches", "(3) front_load", "(4) decomp", "(5) full")

build_decomp <- function(outcomes_named) {
    mods <- list()
    for (y in names(outcomes_named)) {
        nm <- outcomes_named[[y]]
        for (i in seq_along(specs)) {
            mods[[paste0(nm, " | ", sp_sfx[i])]] <- fit_decomp(y, specs[i])
        }
    }
    Filter(Negate(is.null), mods)
}

coef_decomp <- c(

3 ICC Analysis: How Much Variance Do Schedules Explain?

3.1 What the ICC Measures

The Intra-Class Correlation (ICC) answers: of all the variation in an outcome across households and time periods, what fraction is explained by which schedule group the household was assigned to?

We fit a null mixed model for each outcome and grouping dimension a model with only a random intercept for the group, no other predictors:

\[\text{outcome}_{it} = \mu + \alpha_{g(i)} + \varepsilon_{it}\]

where \(\alpha_{g(i)} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\text{between}})\) is a random effect for schedule group \(g\) and \(\varepsilon_{it} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\text{within}})\) is the residual. The ICC is then:

\[\text{ICC} = \frac{\sigma^2_{\text{between}}}{\sigma^2_{\text{between}} + \sigma^2_{\text{within}}}\]

Plain English: ICC is the share of total variance attributable to group membership.

  • ICC = 2% 2% of total variation in the outcome is explained by schedule assignment; the remaining 98% is within-schedule variation (household-to-household differences unrelated to which schedule they received).
  • ICC = 50% equal split between between-schedule and within-schedule variance.
  • ICC = 99% nearly all variation is between schedule groups; households on the same schedule behave almost identically.

Question: Does 1% mean the ratio of variance within a schedule is 1% of across schedules? No. The ICC is the ratio of between-group variance to total variance, not within to between. A 1% ICC means \(\sigma^2_{\text{between}}\) is 1% of total, and \(\sigma^2_{\text{within}}\) is 99% of total i.e., within-schedule variance is about 99 times larger than between-schedule variance, meaning schedules explain very little. (If within were 1% of across, that would correspond to an ICC near 99%, not 1%.)

3.2 How It Is Computed

The ICC is extracted using icc() from the performance package (part of the easystats suite), which is the standard R function for this purpose. It fits the null mixed model via lmer() from lme4 and returns ICC_adjusted = _between / (_between + _within). There is no need for a custom function this is a well-tested, standard computation.

3.3 How to Read the Table

Rows are outcomes grouped by domain. Columns are four different ways of grouping the 20 schedules:

Column Groups What it tests
Raw Schedule (20 groups) 20 distinct schedules Maximum specificity treats each schedule as unique
Volatility (# switches) 3 bins: Low / Medium / High Does how often income switches capture schedule differences?
Timing (Front vs Back) 3 bins: Front / Balanced / Back Does when H draws occur capture schedule differences?
Volatility Front-loading 3 bins of vol_fl Does the composite index capture schedule differences?

What to look for: If the Volatility Front-loading column has a similar ICC to Raw Schedule (20 groups), the composite index captures almost as much schedule-level variance as knowing the exact schedule confirming it is a good summary of what actually differs across schedules. Comparing columns also reveals which dimension (volatility vs timing) is the stronger driver of between-schedule differences.

# Uses performance::icc()  the standard package function.
# For a null mixed model lmer(y ~ 1 + (1|group)), icc()$ICC_adjusted equals
# var_between / (var_between + var_within), which is the standard ICC1.
#
# NAs arise from "singular" lmer fits: when between-group variance is estimated
# as exactly 0, performance::icc() returns NA rather than 0. A singular fit
# simply means no detectable between-group variance, i.e. ICC = 0%, so we
# replace those NAs with 0. Singularity warnings are suppressed accordingly.
calc_icc <- function(outcome, group_var, data) {
    if (!outcome %in% names(data) || !group_var %in% names(data)) return(NA_real_)
    sub <- data[!is.na(data[[outcome]]) & !is.na(data[[group_var]]), ]
    if (nrow(sub) < 10 || sd(sub[[outcome]], na.rm = TRUE) == 0) return(NA_real_)
    tryCatch({
        m <- suppressWarnings(
            lmer(as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ 1 + (1 | ", group_var, ")")),
                 data = sub, REML = TRUE)
        )
        icc_val <- suppressMessages(performance::icc(m)$ICC_adjusted)
        # Singular fit  var_between = 0  ICC = 0, not NA
        if (is.na(icc_val)) 0 else icc_val
    }, error = function(e) NA_real_)
}

grouping_vars   <- c("schedule", "volatility_cat", "timing_cat", "vol_fl_grp")
grouping_labels <- c(
    schedule       = "Raw Schedule\n(20 groups)",
    volatility_cat = "Volatility\n(# switches)",
    timing_cat     = "Timing\n(Front vs Back)",
    vol_fl_grp     = "Volatility  Front-loading\n(composite)"
)

icc_table <- expand.grid(

4 Supporting Analyses

4.1 Dynamic Effects by Period

The period-by-period coefficient plot shows whether the effect of vol_fl accumulates, fades, or reverses across the 6 treatment periods. Each point is an OLS coefficient from a cross-sectional regression within that period; shaded bands are 95% CIs. Each domain uses a fixed y-axis.

run_by_period <- function(outcome, period_val, data) {
    sub <- data %>% filter(period == period_val)
    if (!outcome %in% names(sub) || nrow(sub) < 10) return(NULL)
    fml <- as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ vol_fl_std"))
    tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = sub), error = function(e) NULL)
}

dyn_results <- lapply(reg_outcomes, function(outcome) {
    lapply(1:6, function(p) {
        m <- run_by_period(outcome, p, data_reg)
        if (is.null(m)) return(NULL)
        b  <- coef(m)["vol_fl_std"]
        se <- sqrt(vcov(m)["vol_fl_std", "vol_fl_std"])
        data.frame(outcome = outcome, period = p, coef = b, se = se,
                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
    }) %>% dplyr::bind_rows()
}) %>%
    dplyr::bind_rows() %>%
    mutate(
        OutcomeLabel = factor(reg_labels[outcome], levels = reg_labels[reg_outcomes]),
        Domain = case_when(
            outcome %in% c("phq2_z", "gad2_z")                       ~ "Mental Health",
            outcome %in% c("days_worked", "working_adults_corrected") ~ "Labor",
            outcome %in% c("asset_net_99", "svg_savings_flow_99")     ~ "Assets & Savings",
            TRUE                                                       ~ "Income & Consumption"
        ),
        lo95 = coef - 1.96 * se,
        hi95 = coef + 1.96 * se
    )

plot_domain <- function(domain_name, color_val, ncols = 2) {
    df <- dyn_results %>% filter(Domain == domain_name)
    ggplot(df, aes(x = period, y = coef)) +
        geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray60", linewidth = 0.4) +
        geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lo95, ymax = hi95), fill = color_val, alpha = 0.15) +
        geom_line(color = color_val, linewidth = 0.9) +
        geom_point(color = color_val, size = 2.5) +
        scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:6, labels = paste0("P", 1:6)) +
        facet_wrap(~OutcomeLabel, scales = "fixed", ncol = ncols) +
        labs(
            title    = paste0("Dynamic Effect  ", domain_name),
            subtitle = "OLS per period | SEs clustered at HH | 95% CI shaded",
            x = "Period", y = "Coefficient on vol_fl (std.)"
        ) +
        theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
        theme(
            strip.text       = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            plot.title       = element_text(face = "bold"),
            plot.subtitle    = element_text(size = 8.5, color = "gray40")
        )
}

plot_domain("Mental Health", "#C62828", ncols = 2)

plot_domain("Income & Consumption", "#1976D2", ncols = 3)

plot_domain("Assets & Savings", "#388E3C", ncols = 2)

plot_domain("Labor", "#F57C00", ncols = 2)

4.3 Causal Evidence: Do Work Patterns Causally Affect Mental Health?

Because schedules were randomly assigned within the predictable group, any systematic difference in mental health between schedules must be caused by the schedule itself there is no selection bias. The opposite-pair comparison reinforces this: HHHLLL and LLLHHH receive the same total income but in reverse order. If their MH trajectories mirror each other, it is timing not income level that drives the effect.

We test this formally in three ways:

Test What it asks
F-test (schedule FE) Do the 20 schedules collectively explain MH variation beyond period FE?
Pair-contrast plot For each pair, is MH(front-loaded) MH(complement) 0?
Draw-split contrast Does the MH gap between a pair flip when the front-loaded member switches from H to L draw?

4.3.1 Test 1: Joint F-test

ftest_data <- data_reg

f_results <- lapply(c("phq2_z", "gad2_z"), function(outcome) {
    if (!outcome %in% names(ftest_data)) return(NULL)
    m_full <- tryCatch(
        feols(as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ i(schedule) | period")),
              cluster = ~hh_id, data = ftest_data),
        error = function(e) NULL
    )
    if (is.null(m_full)) return(NULL)
    wt <- tryCatch(wald(m_full, "schedule"), error = function(e) NULL)
    if (is.null(wt)) return(NULL)
    data.frame(
        Outcome = ifelse(outcome == "phq2_z", "Depression (PHQ-2)", "Anxiety (GAD-2)"),
        F_stat  = round(wt$stat, 3),
        df1     = wt$df1,
        df2     = wt$df2,
        p_value = round(wt$p, 4),
        Sig     = ifelse(wt$p < 0.01, "***",
                  ifelse(wt$p < 0.05, "**",
                  ifelse(wt$p < 0.10, "*", ""))),
        stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    )
}) %>% dplyr::bind_rows()

4.3.2 Test 2: Pair-Contrast Plot

For each of the 10 opposite pairs we compute MH = mean MH(front-loaded member) mean MH(back-loaded member). If timing drives MH, this difference should be systematically non-zero.

flip_sched <- function(s) chartr("HL", "LH", s)

sched_meta2 <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period > 0) %>%
    distinct(schedule, vol_fl, front_loading, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    mutate(complement = flip_sched(schedule))

mh_wide <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period >= 1) %>%
    group_by(schedule, period) %>%
    summarise(phq2 = mean(phq2_z, na.rm = TRUE),
              gad2 = mean(gad2_z, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

pairs2 <- sched_meta2 %>%
    filter(schedule < complement) %>%
    left_join(sched_meta2 %>% select(schedule, fl_comp = front_loading),
              by = c("complement" = "schedule")) %>%
    mutate(
        sched_A    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, schedule, complement),
        sched_B    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, complement, schedule),
        pair_label = paste0(sched_A, " vs ", sched_B)
    )

contrasts <- pairs2 %>%
    select(pair_label, sched_A, sched_B, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    left_join(mh_wide %>% rename(sched_A = schedule, phq2_A = phq2, gad2_A = gad2),
              by = "sched_A") %>%
    left_join(mh_wide %>% rename(sched_B = schedule, phq2_B = phq2, gad2_B = gad2),
              by = c("sched_B", "period")) %>%
    mutate(delta_phq2 = phq2_A - phq2_B, delta_gad2 = gad2_A - gad2_B) %>%
    tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = c(delta_phq2, delta_gad2),
                        names_to = "outcome", values_to = "delta") %>%
    mutate(
        OutcomeLabel = ifelse(outcome == "delta_phq2",
                              "Depression (PHQ-2)", "Anxiety (GAD-2)"),
        OutcomeLabel = factor(OutcomeLabel,
                              levels = c("Depression (PHQ-2)", "Anxiety (GAD-2)"))
    )

avg_contrast <- contrasts %>%
    group_by(period, OutcomeLabel) %>%
    summarise(mean_delta = mean(delta, na.rm = TRUE),
              se_delta   = sd(delta, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(sum(!is.na(delta))),
              .groups = "drop") %>%
    mutate(lo = mean_delta - 1.96 * se_delta, hi = mean_delta + 1.96 * se_delta)

ggplot() +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray60", linewidth = 0.4) +
    geom_line(data = contrasts,
              aes(x = period, y = delta, group = pair_label, color = vol_fl_grp),
              alpha = 0.4, linewidth = 0.7) +
    geom_ribbon(data = avg_contrast,
                aes(x = period, ymin = lo, ymax = hi), fill = "gray30", alpha = 0.15) +
    geom_line(data = avg_contrast,
              aes(x = period, y = mean_delta), color = "gray10", linewidth = 1.3) +
    geom_point(data = avg_contrast,
               aes(x = period, y = mean_delta), color = "gray10", size = 3) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:6, labels = paste0("P", 1:6)) +
    scale_color_manual(
        values = c("Low composite" = "#1976D2",
                   "Medium composite" = "#F57C00",
                   "High composite" = "#C62828"),
        name = "Pair composite group"
    ) +
    facet_wrap(~OutcomeLabel, ncol = 2) +
    labs(
        title    = "MH Difference: Front-loaded Schedule minus Back-loaded Complement",
        subtitle = paste0(
            "Thin coloured lines = each of the 10 opposite pairs | ",
            "Thick dark line = average across all pairs (95% CI shaded)\n",
            "Positive delta = front-loaded schedule has higher (worse) MH score"
        ),
        x = "Period", y = "Delta Mean z-score (front-loaded minus back-loaded)"
    ) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
    theme(strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 11),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),

4.3.3 Test 3: Pair-Contrast Regression

flip_sched2 <- function(s) chartr("HL", "LH", s)

sched_meta3 <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period > 0) %>%
    distinct(schedule, vol_fl, front_loading, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    mutate(complement = flip_sched2(schedule))

mh_wide2 <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period >= 1) %>%
    group_by(schedule, period) %>%
    summarise(phq2 = mean(phq2_z, na.rm = TRUE),
              gad2 = mean(gad2_z, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

pairs3 <- sched_meta3 %>%
    filter(schedule < complement) %>%
    left_join(sched_meta3 %>% select(schedule, fl_comp = front_loading),
              by = c("complement" = "schedule")) %>%
    mutate(
        sched_A    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, schedule, complement),
        sched_B    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, complement, schedule),
        pair_label = paste0(sched_A, " vs ", sched_B)
    )

contrasts2 <- pairs3 %>%
    select(pair_label, sched_A, sched_B, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    left_join(mh_wide2 %>% rename(sched_A = schedule, phq2_A = phq2, gad2_A = gad2),
              by = "sched_A") %>%
    left_join(mh_wide2 %>% rename(sched_B = schedule, phq2_B = phq2, gad2_B = gad2),
              by = c("sched_B", "period")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(phq2_A), !is.na(phq2_B), !is.na(gad2_A), !is.na(gad2_B)) %>%
    mutate(delta_phq2 = phq2_A - phq2_B, delta_gad2 = gad2_A - gad2_B)

fit_models <- function(delta_col) {
    df <- contrasts2 %>% rename(delta = !!delta_col) %>%
        mutate(period_f = factor(period))
    list(
        raw   = lm(delta ~ 1, data = df),
        adj   = lm(delta ~ period_f, data = df),
        trend = lm(delta ~ period, data = df)
    )
}

mods_phq2 <- fit_models("delta_phq2")
mods_gad2 <- fit_models("delta_gad2")

tidy_model <- function(m, label) {
    broom::tidy(m, conf.int = TRUE) %>%
        filter(term %in% c("(Intercept)", "period")) %>%
        mutate(
            Model     = label,
            term      = ifelse(term == "(Intercept)", "Mean contrast", "Change per period"),
            estimate  = round(estimate, 4),
            std.error = round(std.error, 4),
            statistic = round(statistic, 3),
            p.value   = round(p.value, 4),
            sig       = ifelse(p.value < 0.01, "***",
                        ifelse(p.value < 0.05, "**",
                        ifelse(p.value < 0.10, "*", "")))
        ) %>%
        select(Model, Coefficient = term, Estimate = estimate,
               SE = std.error, t = statistic, p = p.value, sig)
}

all_results <- bind_rows(
    tidy_model(mods_phq2$raw,   "PHQ-2: raw mean"),
    tidy_model(mods_phq2$adj,   "PHQ-2: period-adj"),
    tidy_model(mods_phq2$trend, "PHQ-2: time trend"),
    tidy_model(mods_gad2$raw,   "GAD-2: raw mean"),
    tidy_model(mods_gad2$adj,   "GAD-2: period-adj"),
    tidy_model(mods_gad2$trend, "GAD-2: time trend")
)
print(knitr::kable(all_results,
      caption = "Pair Contrast Regression: Front-loaded minus Back-loaded Complement"))

4.3.4 Test 4: Period-Aware Contrast (Split by Current Draw)

For a pair like HHHLLL vs LLLHHH, the overall mean contrast averages across periods where the front-loaded schedule is currently in a High draw AND periods where it is in a Low draw effects that may cancel. The sharper test labels each observation by the front-loaded members current draw state and checks whether the MH gap flips accordingly.

draw_seq <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period >= 1) %>%
    group_by(schedule, period) %>%
    summarise(draw = round(mean(high_draw, na.rm = TRUE)), .groups = "drop")

flip_sched3 <- function(s) chartr("HL", "LH", s)

sched_meta4 <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period > 0) %>%
    distinct(schedule, front_loading, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    mutate(complement = flip_sched3(schedule))

pairs4 <- sched_meta4 %>%
    filter(schedule < complement) %>%
    left_join(sched_meta4 %>% select(schedule, fl_comp = front_loading),
              by = c("complement" = "schedule")) %>%
    mutate(
        sched_A    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, schedule, complement),
        sched_B    = ifelse(front_loading >= fl_comp, complement, schedule),
        pair_label = paste0(sched_A, " vs ", sched_B)
    )

mh_wide3 <- data_analysis %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period >= 1) %>%
    group_by(schedule, period) %>%
    summarise(phq2 = mean(phq2_z, na.rm = TRUE),
              gad2 = mean(gad2_z, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

contrasts3 <- pairs4 %>%
    select(pair_label, sched_A, sched_B, vol_fl_grp) %>%
    left_join(mh_wide3 %>% rename(sched_A = schedule, phq2_A = phq2, gad2_A = gad2),
              by = "sched_A") %>%
    left_join(mh_wide3 %>% rename(sched_B = schedule, phq2_B = phq2, gad2_B = gad2),
              by = c("sched_B", "period")) %>%
    left_join(draw_seq %>% rename(sched_A = schedule, draw_A = draw),
              by = c("sched_A", "period")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(phq2_A), !is.na(phq2_B), !is.na(draw_A)) %>%
    mutate(
        delta_phq2 = phq2_A - phq2_B,
        delta_gad2 = gad2_A - gad2_B,
        draw_state = ifelse(draw_A == 1,
            "A gets H (front-loaded advantage)",
            "A gets L (front-loaded disadvantage)")
    )

draw_summary <- contrasts3 %>%
    group_by(draw_state) %>%
    summarise(n         = n(),
              mean_phq2 = round(mean(delta_phq2, na.rm = TRUE), 4),
              se_phq2   = round(sd(delta_phq2, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(n()), 4),
              mean_gad2 = round(mean(delta_gad2, na.rm = TRUE), 4),
              se_gad2   = round(sd(delta_gad2, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(n()), 4),
              .groups   = "drop")
print(knitr::kable(draw_summary,
      caption = "Mean delta (front-loaded minus back-loaded) by current draw type"))

    tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = c(delta_phq2, delta_gad2),
                        names_to = "outcome", values_to = "delta") %>%
    mutate(
        OutcomeLabel = ifelse(outcome == "delta_phq2",
                              "Depression (PHQ-2)", "Anxiety (GAD-2)"),
        OutcomeLabel = factor(OutcomeLabel,
                              levels = c("Depression (PHQ-2)", "Anxiety (GAD-2)"))
    )

avg_by_draw <- contrasts3_long %>%
    group_by(period, draw_state, OutcomeLabel) %>%
    summarise(mean_d = mean(delta, na.rm = TRUE),
              se_d   = sd(delta, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(n()),
              .groups = "drop") %>%
    mutate(lo = mean_d - 1.96 * se_d, hi = mean_d + 1.96 * se_d)

ggplot(avg_by_draw,

4.4 Robustness: Is the Income Effect from Schedule Shape or the Current Draw?

Is the positive vol_fl coefficient on total income a genuine schedule-shape effect, or does it just mechanically track the current draw (H draw periods mechanically have higher income regardless of schedule shape)? We add high_draw as a control this is the same logic as column (5) in the decomposition table above, presented here separately for all outcome panels.

panel_a <- c(phq2_z = "Depression (PHQ-2)", gad2_z = "Anxiety (GAD-2)")

panel_b1_raw <- c("total_income_99", "total_consumption_99", "food_consumption_total_99",
                  "loan_total_outstanding_99", "svg_savings_flow_99", "asset_net_99")
panel_b2_raw <- c("days_worked", "working_adults_corrected")

panel_b_labels_all <- c(reg_labels,
    loan_total_outstanding_99 = "Loan Outstanding",
    days_worked               = "Days Worked",
    working_adults_corrected  = "Working Adults")
mk_panel <- function(vars) {
    out <- setNames(panel_b_labels_all[vars], vars)
    out[is.na(out)] <- vars[is.na(out)]
    out
}
panel_b1 <- mk_panel(panel_b1_raw)
panel_b2 <- mk_panel(panel_b2_raw)

fit_rob <- function(y, spec, dat = data_reg) {
    fml <- switch(spec,
        vfl  = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ vol_fl_std | period")),
        hd   = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ high_draw   | period")),
        both = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ vol_fl_std + high_draw | period")))
    tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = dat), error = function(e) NULL)
}

build_mods <- function(outcomes_named) {
    mods <- list()
    for (y in names(outcomes_named)) {
        nm <- outcomes_named[[y]]
        mods[[paste0(nm, " | vol_fl")]]    <- fit_rob(y, "vfl")
        mods[[paste0(nm, " | high_draw")]] <- fit_rob(y, "hd")
        mods[[paste0(nm, " | both")]]      <- fit_rob(y, "both")
    }
    Filter(Negate(is.null), mods)
}

coef_map_rob <- c("vol_fl_std" = "vol_fl (std.)  schedule shape",
                  "high_draw"  = "High draw (current period)")
notes_rob <- paste0(
    "Predictable group, periods 1-6. Period FE. SEs clustered at HH. ",
    "Each outcome: (1) vol_fl only; (2) high_draw only; (3) both. ",
    "Key test: if vol_fl survives in 'both', schedule shape has an independent effect.")
